      <Subject xmlns="urn:xmlns:nl:pop-project:vocab:Subjects#">D13600</Subject>
      <Abstract xml:lang="en">The goal of the project is to determine the changes in the coordination environment of Ni-containing catalysts for epoxidation and polymerization in the solid state, in solution and on a polymeric support on the basis of novel approach for X-ray absorption spectroscopy (XAS) theoretical analysis using state-of-the-art parallel computer simulations. The Ni catalysts for two reactions will be investigated, viz. i) the polymerization of isocyanides by Ni perchlorate to give polyimides, and ii) the so-called Mukaiyama epoxidation, i.e. the reductive activation by Ni(acac) (acac = acetylacetonate) complexes of molecular oxygen with an aldehyde yielding epoxide from alkene. i) The Ni-catalyzed polymerization of isocyanides results in polyimides which have unique properties like rigidity and controlled chirality. Polymerization is proposed to proceed by coordination of 4 isocyanide molecules to Ni in a square-planar geometry and subsequent initiation by attack of a nucleophile on one of the coordinated monomers. The only established crystal structure, however, is of a Ni complex with a bulky isocyanide whose polymerization is hindered for sterical reasons. ii) Depending on the solvent, non-substituted Ni-acac complexes in solution are subject to association equilibria to form trimers of formula [Ni3(acac)6] in which Ni is coordinatively saturated. This makes it less reactive (at high concentrations) than Ni(acac)2 complexes with bulky substituents in which the equilibrium is shifted to the monomer side so that Ni exists in a square-planar 4-coordinate complex, with 2 open coordination sites. The Nijmegen group has started a programme to elucidate the mechanism of these catalytic reactions by XAS, and some data, viz. of the Ni complex with acac or non-polymerizable and polymerizable (isoamyl) isocyanide diluted in boron nitride and in solution, in the presence or absence of initiator, grafted onto a polymeric benzimidazole support, and at various temperatures, have been taken at the SRS, Daresbury Laboratory, UK. Additional data, including solvent variation, will be taken in 2003 at the DUBBLE station at the ESRF, Grenoble, France. Two parts of XAS spectra contain complementary information; EXAFS has ligand types, distances, and coordination numbers, whereas XANES has metal valence and full coordination geometry including bond angles. Nijmegen has expertise in EXAFS analysis of the catalysts. The Rostov group now develops a novel approach to simulate the XANES by fitting theoretical spectra to the experimental data using state-of-the art parallel computing algorithms within the full multiple scattering framework initially proposed for biological substances but recently also extended to small nanoclusters. In view of the complimentarity it is important that the starting models for the coordination that are used in the XANES calculations are consistent with the EXAFS results. It is therefore essential that a close collaboration on this problem between Nijmegen and Rostov is established, and this is also expected to enhance the level of expertise of XANES interpretation in Nijmegen, and of EXAFS interpretation in Rostov.</Abstract>
